{
  "title": "Operation and Time",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f030e172a675d229",
      "text": "A second innovation (or perhaps just: specification) is that systems theory asks about the operation that produces and reproduces the difference of system and environment. Systems are thus referred to as forms, forms as differences, and differences by the mode of operation that leads to the production and maintenance of the difference of system and environment. This is, as might be shown by the relation between operation and time, a quite unclassical way of describing reality. The tradition, from Aristotle to Hegel, had described time by means of the distinction between being and non-being (i.e., ontologically) and had conceived it (with considerable uncertainties/ambiguities in its formulation) as the unity of being and non-being. For the resolution of this paradox then the concept of movement had served, and in another way also chronometry. But if all this is not to be valid any more: what is valid then?\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7268521eaf3e2182",
      "text": "We begin with the concept of operation, i.e. with the concept of an [[event]] without time permanence. Time permanence can only be achieved recursively, only by interconnection with other events, i.e. only by system formation, which selectively constitutes the operations that are suitable for this purpose and thus distinguishes itself from the environment of what is not considered. The operation by which social systems and consequently society are constituted is communication. Whenever communication comes about, society is formed, just as, conversely, communication can never occur as a solitary event, but only by recourse to and anticipation of other communications, i.e. only in society."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "efc081f1b30be672",
      "text": "If we consider this operational determination of system formation together with the differentiation theory, this has a far-reaching result – far-reaching at least in the sense of a correction of the prevailing use of language. We see that the subsystems also depend on the mode of operation of the system as a whole, in our case also the political system on the mode of operation communication; and from this follows that the subsystems also participate operatively in the reproduction of the system as a whole, that is, that political communication accomplishes society. Formulas like \"state and society\" or \"politics and society\" thus lose their meaning. It is not a matter of mutually exclusive facts that could be juxtaposed. Nor is it a matter, in systems theory terms, of a relationship between system and environment. It is true that the political system divides society into political system and environment (just as society divides the world into communication and non-communication). But society is then both: the political system itself and its environment within society. There is communication inside and outside. This then leads to the question, which we will explore in wide-ranging investigations below: how then the specificity of politics differs from other social communication: by a particular medium (chapter 2), by a particular function (chapter 3), by a particular encoding (chapter 3), or by all of these together?"
    },
