        "text": "If we consider this operational determination of system formation together with the differentiation theory, this has a far-reaching result - far-reaching at least in the sense of a correction of the prevailing use of language. We see that the subsystems also depend on the mode of operation of the system as a whole, in our case also the political system on the mode of operation communication; and from this follows that the subsystems also participate operatively in the reproduction of the system as a whole, that is, that political communication accomplishes society. Formulas like \"state and society\" or \"politics and society\" thus lose their meaning. It is not a matter of mutually exclusive facts that could be juxtaposed. Nor is it a matter, in systems theory terms, of a relationship between system and environment. It is true that the political system divides society into political system and environment (just as society divides the world into communication and non-communication). But society is then both: the political system itself and its environment within society. There is communication inside and outside. This then leads to the question, which we will explore in wide-ranging investigations below: how then the specificity of politics differs from other social communication: by a particular medium (chapter 2), by a particular function (chapter 3), by a particular encoding (chapterz), or by all of these together?"
